  "notes": "TASK A caveats: (1) pop2011, literacyPct, sexRatio and urbanPct verified against Census 2011 tables (census2011.co.in district pages, which reproduce official PCA data); the official censusindia.gov.in PCA Highlights PDF for Karnataka is a scanned document and could not be text-verified directly. (2) Boundary basis is the current 31-district map: Ballari figures are post-2021 residual (pop 1,400,970; 43.37% urban; sex ratio 984, per Wikipedia's census-derived recomputation); Vijayanagara (created Nov 2021) 2011-equivalent pop 1,353,628, 26.57% urban, sex ratio 976 — its literacyPct is omitted because no official recomputed figure exists (likely ~63-66%, between Yadgir-belt and residual Ballari levels; do not treat as verified). Ballari's literacyPct 67.43 and Davanagere's 75.74 are the pre-split/undivided values applied to the new boundaries — approximate. Davanagere pop2011/urbanPct/sexRatio reflect post-2019 transfer of Harapanahalli taluk to (now) Vijayanagara. (3) popEstimate = unofficial ~2025-26 projections; Census 2021 was never conducted, and no official district-level projections exist. Figures were derived by extrapolating 2001-11 district growth rates with tapering, constrained to the NCP state projection of roughly 69-70.5 million for Karnataka in 2026; treat as ±5-10%, Bengaluru Urban most uncertain (13-14.5M range commonly cited). (4) Ramanagara was officially renamed Bengaluru South district in 2024. North-east districts (Yadgir, Raichur, Koppal, Kalaburagi, Vijayapura, Ballari) grow fastest ex-Bengaluru; Kodagu, Chikkamagaluru, Mandya, Hassan, Udupi are near-stagnant or declining. TASK B notes: Religion mix per Census 2011 Karnataka: Hindu 84.00%, Muslim 12.92%, Christian 1.87% — matches the requested sampling weights. Regional flavor: south/Old Mysuru male names favor -swamy/-anna/-aiah/-egowda endings and heavy initials use (Puttaswamy, Shivanna, Devegowda); north Karnataka (Kittur + Kalyana Karnataka) favors -appa/-avva endings and Basava/Sharana/Siddha (Lingayat) and Hanamant/Yallappa themes (Basavaraj, Sharanappa, Ningavva); coastal (DK/Udupi) uses Bunt/Billava/Mogaveera surnames (Shetty, Rai, Poojary, Salian, Kotian, Suvarna) and GSB surnames (Pai, Kamath, Shenoy, Prabhu, Kini, Baliga). -amma/-avva female forms skew to older rural cohorts; modern female names (Shruthi, Meghana, Chaitra) skew under-40 urban. Muslim usage: north-Karnataka rural Muslim men often carry the suffix 'Sab/Saab' (Hussainsab, Imamsab) or occupational surnames (Mulla, Nadaf, Bagwan, Mujawar, Killedar); Bengaluru/Mysuru Muslims commonly use 'Pasha' and 'Khan'; coastal Beary Muslims use forms like Fathuma, Bappa, and names ending -ichcha. Mangaluru Christians (Mangalorean Catholics) pair Western first names with Luso-Konkani surnames (D'Souza, Fernandes, Pinto, Lobo, Rodrigues, Pereira, Mascarenhas, Sequeira, Menezes). Name lists are compiled from general knowledge of Karnataka onomastics, not from a verified frequency corpus — no official first-name frequency data exists; treat relative frequencies as indicative.",
